That&amp;#x27;s a really important observation about Luna getting up at night to drink—that definitely adds to the concern and indicates how much thirst she&amp;#x27;s experiencing.

For these types of symptoms, it&amp;#x27;s actually really important **not** to limit her water intake. Her body is likely trying to compensate for something, and restricting water could make her feel worse or even be dangerous. Measuring her water intake is a great idea to tell the vet exactly how much she&#x27;s drinking.

Right now, the most crucial step is to get Luna to a veterinarian as quickly as possible. Changes to her food or other home care aren&#x27;t recommended without a diagnosis from a vet, as they need to figure out the underlying cause first. Your vet will be able to give you specific guidance on diet and care once they know what&#x27;s going on.

Please focus on getting her seen by a vet right away.&lt;/blockquote&gt;

⚠️ &lt;i&gt;Please seek immediate vet care first&lt;/i&gt;</blockquote>

